<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/7057> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #7057" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/5> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "A certain P. Vatienus is named in a Roman sepulchral inscription (Bull. Com. 56, 1928, 293; cf. CIL 6.39023, a freedman). Both inscriptions are cited by Syme, Historia 5, 1956, 208RP 1.320. He may be a grandson of P. Vatienus of Reate to whom the Dioscuri revealed the victory at Pydna (Cic. ND 2.6; 3.11 and 13, with the reading Vatinius; cf. Val. Max. 1.8.4, where most manuscripts read Vatinius with the variant Vacienus; Lactant. 2.7.10, vatieno), but the possibility that he was a senator depends on CIL 1(2).821-ILLRP 384: [Corn]elia L. Scipion[is f.] Vatieni. As the youthful interlocutor in the De Natura Deorum (dramatic date 76) was also a son-in-law of the consul of 83, he had good prospects of a senatorial career. In any case, Vatinius seems excluded both as the inferior reading in the passages of Cicero and as a man whose grandfather was not a citizen (note Act. Tr. for 42, where the grandfather's praenomen is lacking). (LRT) See Wiseman, NM 270, no. 466.\n" .
